30|$|Alcohol 2 a {{was next}} {{converted}} to aldehyde 3 by Ley-Griffith oxidation (TPAP, NMO, MS 4 A) (Griffith et al. 1987; Ley et al. 1994) in 60  % yield. Wittig reaction of aldehyde 3 with <b>tert-butyl</b> (<b>triphenylphosphoranylidene)acetate</b> in CH 2 Cl 2 gave α,β-unsaturated ester 4 in 92  % yield with exclusive (E)-selectivity. The molecular framework of HMG was thus constructed in these four-step reactions.|$|E
30|$|To a stirred {{solution}} of aldehyde 3 (350  mg, 1.14  mmol) in CH 2 Cl 2 (10  mL) at 35  °C were added <b>tert-butyl</b> (<b>triphenylphosphoranylidene)acetate</b> (643  mg, 1.71  mmol). After 2  h, the mixture was concentrated in vacuo. The residue was purified by silica gel column chromatography (10  g, EtOAc/hexane =  2 : 8) to give diastereomerically pure α,β-unsaturated ester 4 (422  mg, 92  %) {{as a white}} solid: IR (KBr) 3385, 2979, 2932, 2870, 1706  cm− 1; 1 H NMR (400  MHz, CDCl 3) δ 7.54 – 7.40 (m, 5 H), 6.80 (d, J =  16.2  Hz, 1 H), 5.94 (d, J =  16.2  Hz, 1 H), 5.52 (s, 1 H), 4.33 (d, J =  10.6  Hz, 2 H), 3.89 (d, J =  11.5  Hz, 2 H), 1.51 (s, 9 H), 1.48 (s, 9 H); 13 C NMR (100  MHz, CDCl 3) δ 165.1, 154.7, 143.6, 137.3, 129.4, 128.4 (× 2), 126.0 (× 2), 124.2, 101.8, 80.9, 80.1, 72.1, 53.2 (× 2), 28.4 (× 3), 28.1 (× 3).|$|E

